 the Artist Persona -- t16. Peter Greenaway’s Artist-Entrepreneurs -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnlike most studies of the relationship between cinema and art, which privilege questions of medium or institutional specificity and intermediality, Screening the Art World explores the ways in which artists and the art world more generally have been represented in cinema. Contributors address a rarely explored subject -art in cinema, rather than the art of cinema - by considering films across genres, historical periods and national cinemas in order to reflect on cinema’s fluctuating imaginary of ‘art’ and ‘the art world’. The book examines the intersection of art history with history in cinema, cinema’s simultaneous affirmation and denigration of the idea of art as ‘truth’ and what this means for cinema’s understanding of itself, the dominant, often contradictory ways in which artists have been represented on screen, and cinematic representations of the art world’s tenuous position between commercial good and cultural capital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictures and the arts. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aHistory. 4aMedia Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  acinema, visual arts, aesthetics.1 aBarber, Bruce A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDell’Aria, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelleman, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlynn, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Kelly, econtributor.